/>&gt; Well, 'mem=2048M' shouldn't really limit device memory, it's supposed to limit<br />&gt; (trim) 'RAM' and not much else.<br /><br />Agreed. You should very much be able to map in IO memory or whatever<br />above the 2G address even if the high_memory itself might be limited<br />to 2GB.<br /><br />So I think that commit ce56a86e2ade ("x86/mm: Limit mmap() of /dev/mem<br />to valid physical addresses") is wrong, in that "high_memory" is very<br />much the wrong thing to test.<br /><br />The memory mapping limit might validly be something like<br /><br />   1ull &lt;&lt; boot_cpu_data.x86_phys_bits<br /><br />or similar, but for now I suspect that the right thing to do is to<br />revert. I'm not convinced that our "x86_phys_bits" value is guaranteed<br />to be always right, since I think we mainlyjust use it for showing<br />things, rather than have lots of code that depends on it.<br /><br />Ingo?<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
